entry.title: Split ORB "v0.2" into script- and non-script initiated fetches.
entry.content:
ORB "v0.2" implemented ORB-style error handling, by injecting a

network error instead of an empty response. This causes errors

(in the wild and in the WPT test suite). Another browser solved

this problem by splitting this up, and doing proper ORB-style

error handling for everything except script-initiated fetches.

This resolves the immediate compatibility issues.



Here, we split ORB "v0.2" along this line: Have an "v0.2" flag

for ORB-style error handling (except for script-initiated fetches),

and an "errors-for-all-fetches" version that implements full ORB-style

error handling.

entry.title: [UPMLocalPwd] Fix the frozen progress bar in the export flow
entry.content:
The problem: The ExportFlow is not supposed to start the serialization

until the passwords are fetched from the password store. For this

reason, the parameter passwordsAvailable was introduced into the

ExportFlow.startExporting. In the case when startExporting is called

before passwords are available, PasswordManagerHandlerProvider will

notify the PasswordMigrationWarningMediator when the passwords are

fetched and the mediator will trigger the serialization on the export

flow. The problem now is that we rely on that the passwordListAvailable

will always be triggered, which is not the case. It's possible that our

subscription to the PMHP happens after the passwords have been fetched.



The solution: Introduce the isWaitingForPasswordStore in the

PasswordManagerHandler and check it when starting the export flow.

entry.title: Convert CloneChildrenFlag to NodeCloningData
entry.content:
This is part 1 of a 2-part CL, which adds state to the `Clone()`

operation. To add the ability to clone DOM Parts, more state needs

to be kept during the cloning tree walk. For example, when a Node

is cloned, if that Node is used by a DOM Part, we need to keep a

reference to connect the original Node to the cloned Node, so that

the Part can be cloned and made to point to the cloned Node.



This CL does not modify any DOM Part related behavior. It simply

sets the stage by replacing the enum CloneChildrenFlag with a new

NodeCloningData object. For now, that object just contains the

equivalent bits from CloneChildrenFlag, split out as an EnumSet.

This:



```

enum class CloneChildrenFlag { kSkip, kClone, kCloneWithShadows };

```



becomes this:



```

enum class CloneOption {

kIncludeChildren,

kIncludeShadowRoots,

};

using CloneOptionSet = base::EnumSet;

```



which is equivalent in terms of how the old enum was used.



A followup CL [1] will add more state to NodeCloningData, including

another option in `CloneOption`. This CL should not affect behavior in

any way.

entry.title: [ios][web] Initialize SerializedData from protobuf message
entry.content:
Change SerializedData to be initialized from protobuf message. This

simplify the implementation of SerializedData since all data is now

accessible from the WebStateMetadataStorage.



With the optimised serialisation storage, the data won't be loaded

until the WebState becomes realized, so the SerializedData takes a

callback to load the data.

to limit how much is stored in memory at the same time when using

the non-optimised session serialisation code.

entry.title: Fix DevUi tests.
entry.content:
This change started as a fix for the permission UI dialog, but expanded

to clear other flakiness issues with the devui tests as well.



The issue with the popup was solved by accessing the preferences for

`MainActivity` through `ContextUtils.getApplicationContext` instead of

using the `Activity#getPreferences` method, as the former handles

the test injection of in-memory preferences correctly.

The actual preferences file has not changed, as the implementation in

Activity also uses the `getLocalClassName()` method to obtain the

file name. This change allowed the test to set the preferences for

the class.



Flakiness was in part caused by the erroneous use of

`ViewUtils.waitForView`, which does not actually do a synchronous wait

when called directly. This has been replaced by the recommended way of

waiting

`onView(isRoot()).check(ViewUtils.waitForView...)`

in some cases, and in other cases simply by

`onView(...).check(matches(isVisible()))`.



Other test issues have been solved by disabling batching.



The CL also migrates away from using InstrumentationRegistry.

entry.title: Revamp the Cronet telemetry manifest flag
entry.content:
Before:







After:











The rationale is as follows:



- The meta-data entries are moved to a "meta-data holder service" as application-level meta-data tends to cause scalability issues with PackageManager queries.



- The prefix is changed from "org.chromium.net" to "android.net.http" to make the names look less jarring when using Cronet in AOSP (i.e. HttpEngine). This means the AOSP prefix is also used even when using the Chromium variant of Cronet, but that seems more tolerable. We could also keep using the Chromium prefix in Chromium and adjust it downstream in AOSP, but that would add complexity for little benefit.



- The name "Cronet" is removed because that is redundant with the "android.net.http" prefix, and AOSP surfaces are not supposed to use the term "Cronet".



This change is safe from a backwards compatibility perspective because no apps use this flag today, except for one (AGSA), which has been adjusted to specify both the old and new meta-data entries so that it will behave correctly regardless of which Cronet version it's using.



We take the opportunity to also simplify the test code - we can simply replace the entire meta-data object instead of "patching" it because Cronet owns the entire Bundle.

entry.title: media/gpu: Add Tile4 support to VA-API WebP and JPEG Decoding Tests
entry.content:
Add some utilities to map Tile4 buffers in the VA-API WebP and JPEG

DMAbuf export unittests. Currently these tests assume that the exported

DMA buffer is mappable by importing into minigbm, but some newer

platforms use Tile4 formatted buffers that aren't directly mappable.

This patch works around the issue by forcibly mapping the buffers

linearly and then manually detiling the pixel data in a userspace

utility function.



Note that we opted not to expose this functionality directly through

minigbm, because we decided this should be a test-only path for the time

being.

entry.title: Removed redundant check in renderer filling logic
entry.content:
ForEachMatchingFormFieldCommon stores the element that were filled in a

list matched_fields that it returns by the end of the function.



While iterating over the fields in `data` to find the corresponding

blink element and fill it, there's a heuristic check that breaks out of

the loop if matching_fields has the same size as the list of blink

elements.



Regardless of the fact that this check isn't really necessary, it is not

quite useful because during that loop only the initiating element is

added to the list and nothing else, which considerably narrows the scope

where this check is useful, which are single-field forms.



This CL removes this check for simplicity, and fixes tests that were

relying on it.

entry.title: [autofill] Hide delete autocomplete button on arrow navigation to a different cell.
entry.content:
prior to this CL navigating to different cells (arrow key up or down), could lead to the button still being visible if the mouse cursor was kept on above a previously selected cell.



The culprit was an unnecessary IsMouseHovered condition. Now we always hide or show the button based on `selected` value.



This CL also gets rid of listening to state changes and instead, uses OnMouseEntered/Exited to run the select/unselect callback.



before:https://screencast.googleplex.com/cast/NjExOTU0NDUyODU2ODMyMHwyZDdhNDk0MC01Yw



Note how when the mouse cursor is above a row and an arrow navigation happen, the cell is unselected but the button remains visible.





after: https://screencast.googleplex.com/cast/NTA2MTc0ODc0MzczMzI0OHwyNDUwZGMzZi1hYQ

entry.content:

getting a onTrimMemory() call. But when the feature is enabled, the next

call to onTrimMemory() will have a null draw functor, and thus not

record a metric, whereas the other path would.



This leads to sample imbalance in the control and experimental groups.
